story_txt:
Acquired Brain Injury Rehab was not in Thomas Evers' plans....But after a near drowning in Cancun, and Thomas being pulled from the pool without vital signs, Thomas and his family have a long road through rehabilitation.  Since the accident on March 12th, Thomas spent 4 days in a Mexican ICU, 5 days in Toronto Sick Children's ICU and 17 days in a general Sick Kids ward. On April 7, Thomas was moved to Holland-Bloorview Kids Rehabilitation Hospital where his initial therapy plan has him scheduled to remain as an in-patient through the end of August.Thomas is a young and active teen, who plays basketball for his high school, coaches soccer and works at a local Pita place.  He has also been accepted to 4 universities that offer a Business program. (  Brock, Guelph-Humber, Carlton and St Mary's) He now uses all that energy and drive to overcome the hurdles thrown in his path.Joe and Sandy have not left his side for a minute since that day. They encourage and cheer him on as he works towards a full recovery! This determination shows through the huge strides he has already taken!Since leaving Sick Kids ICU , Thomas has made some great progress:

he had just been extubated and initially had some difficulty breathing, now lungs are clear;


he had a feeding tube...but quickly moved to puree, soft foods and now on regular food;


he couldn't sit up, now he quickly sits up in bed and rolls to sit at the edge of the bed;


he couldn't move his toes or legs....now he stands up and walks...he can bend over and pick up things from the floor;


he couldn't talk...his speech therapy has given him some words and techniques;


he could hardly lift his arms or clench a fist...he now plays mini basketball catch and Velcro paddle ball with dad and mom!

The hope is that Thomas can make similar progress on the neurological improvements. He has difficulty remembering the current date and where he is. The brain injury currently manifests itself with delusions, short attention span and the need for simple, single step instructions.  Medical staff said this will be a marathon for improvement;at Thomas' body's pace-with times of two steps forward and one back.  The stretch-goal hope that he recovers sufficiently to attend one of the universities at a later date.Joe and Sandy plan to continue to work with him for the months to come.  To do this,  they have decided that Joe is taking an unpaid  leave from work as IMAX Corp's VP Information Systems with full support from IMAX.As the Evers family looks ahead, they can anticipate regular and new bills to start building.  There is an estimate of 2-3 years of recovery time expected. This will erode into their savings. This fundraising is our attempt to help stem some of that expense. Some may choose to use interac to Aunt Yvonne's email yvonne.steer@hotmail.comTogether, we are Team Thomas!To support the cause and spread the word, we have Team Thomas stickers and T-shirts. (See the Perks section on how to get yours).
